##############################################################
#
#  Setup
#
#

Context("Numeric");
#given
$H= random(15,20,0.5) ;# [ft]
$Q= random(10000,15000,500);# [gal/min]

#computation
$ht=150-25-$H;# [ft]
$hhp=150+$H-25;# [ft]
$QC= $Q*0.0022;# [ft^3/s]
$Ans1= 62.4*$QC*$ht;# [ ft.lbf/s]
$Ans2=$hhp*62.4*$QC;# [ft.lbf/s]

#set tolerance
Context()->flags->set(
tolerance=>.02,);

##############################################################
#
#  PGML 
#
#

BEGIN_PGML

[@ image("UBC-FLU-18-038.png", width=>[$width], height=>[$height]) @]*

The pump-turbine system illustrated in the diagram is used to produce power for a city. During the day power is generated by the water running the pump (like the turbine of a dam) as it flows from the upper reservoir to the one below. During the night, the pump is powered to pump water from the lower reservoir to the upper reservoirs to allow for power generation the next day. The flow rate is the same in either directaion at [`[$Q]`] [`gal/min`], and the friction head loss is [`[$H]`] [`ft`]. What is the power: 
1. Extracted by the turbine?  
2. Delivered by the pump?  

[`P_{turbine}=`] [____]{"$Ans1"} [`ft\cdot lbf/s`]  
[`P_{pump}=`] [____]{"$Ans2"} [`ft\cdot lbf/s`]

END_PGML

